  <!-- ── Centrifuge Separation ── -->
  <h2 id="centrifuge-separation">How a Disc Stack Centrifuge Separates Emulsified Water</h2>

  <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start mb-6">
    <div class="md:w-[40%] shrink-0">
      <img
        src="/images/waste-oil-emulsion-centrifuge/Waste-Oil-Centrifuge-Alfa-Laval-MOPX209.webp"
        alt="Waste Oil Centrifuge Alfa Laval MOPX209"
        width="400"
        height="350"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-sm w-full h-auto object-contain"
      />
      <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-1 text-center">Alfa Laval MOPX-209 disc stack centrifuge for waste oil emulsion breaking</p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex-1 min-w-0">
      <p class="mb-4">
        A self-cleaning disc stack centrifuge separates emulsified water from waste oil through intense centrifugal force applied across a thin-film flow path. The process works as follows:
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <ol>
    <li>Waste oil is <strong>pre-heated</strong> to reduce viscosity and weaken the emulsion's interfacial film (typically 180–200&deg;F)</li>
    <li>The heated oil enters the <strong>centrifuge bowl</strong>, which spins at high speed, generating thousands of Gs of centrifugal force</li>
    <li>Inside the bowl, a <strong>disc stack</strong> (a series of conical discs) creates thin-film channels that dramatically shorten the settling distance for water droplets</li>
    <li>The intense G-force overcomes the interfacial tension holding water droplets in suspension, forcing them to <strong>coalesce and migrate</strong> toward the bowl periphery</li>
    <li>Separated water (heavy phase) discharges through a dedicated outlet, while clean oil (light phase) exits through a separate outlet</li>
    <li>Accumulated solids are <strong>automatically ejected</strong> through the self-cleaning mechanism at timed intervals</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The combination of <strong>high temperature</strong> and <strong>high centrifugal force</strong> is the key to effective emulsion breaking. Temperature weakens the emulsion, while centrifugal force provides the mechanical energy to complete the separation.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Case Study ── -->
  <h2 id="case-study">Case Study: Guam Waste Oil Recovery</h2>

  <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start mb-6">
